  "footnotes": [
    "Anuradhapura kingdom (c.377 BCE–1017 CE): one of the longest-lasting kingdoms in Asian history; its massive dagobas (stupas) and sophisticated irrigation tank system (wewa) supported a civilization of perhaps 2 million; Theravada Buddhism was introduced from India during the reign of Devanampiya Tissa (c.250 BCE) and became central to Sinhalese identity",
    "Chola conquest (1017–1070): the South Indian Chola Empire under Rajendra I conquered Anuradhapura and moved the capital to Polonnaruwa; Vijayabahu I liberated the island in 1070 from Ruhuna, establishing the Polonnaruwa period; this Chola interlude deeply shaped Tamil-Sinhalese ethnic dynamics",
    "Polonnaruwa and Parakramabahu I (r.1153–1186): the greatest medieval Sinhalese king; he unified the island, reformed the sangha (Buddhist monastic order), built the Parakrama Samudra reservoir, and even launched an overseas expedition to Burma; Polonnaruwa's ruins are a UNESCO World Heritage site",
    "Jaffna kingdom (c.1215–1619): the most significant Tamil polity in Sri Lankan history, ruled by the Aryacakravarti dynasty; it controlled the northern peninsula and maintained close ties with South Indian Tamil kingdoms; Portuguese conquest in 1619 ended Tamil political independence in Sri Lanka",
    "Kandy kingdom (1469–1815): the last independent Sinhalese kingdom, surviving in the central highlands for over three centuries; it resisted Portuguese, Dutch, and initially British colonizers; the Sacred Tooth Relic of the Buddha in Kandy remains the most sacred object in Sinhalese Buddhism; British annexation in 1815 ended 2,300 years of indigenous monarchy",
    "British Ceylon (1796–1948): the British unified the island under one administration for the first time; they introduced plantation agriculture (coffee, then tea after the 1869 blight), building roads and railways; they also brought Tamil laborers from South India, creating the 'estate Tamil' community distinct from the indigenous Jaffna Tamils",
    "Sri Lankan Civil War (1983–2009): decades of ethnic tension between the Sinhalese majority and Tamil minority erupted into full civil war; the LTTE (Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam) fought for an independent Tamil state in the north and east; the war ended with the LTTE's military defeat in 2009, but ethnic reconciliation remains incomplete"
  ]
